Certainly! When collecting sensitive information like a document or identification number, it's crucial to implement robust input validation both on the client side and the server side to enhance security. Here’s how you can achieve this:

### Client-Side Validation

Client-side validation helps prevent invalid data from reaching the server, improving the user experience and reducing the load on the server. You can use JavaScript to validate the input fields.

### Server-Side Validation

Server-side validation is essential because client-side validation can be bypassed. It ensures that the data is valid even if the client-side validation fails.

### Example Implementation

Let's enhance the previous form example to include both client-side and server-side validation.

#### HTML and Basic Styling

First, let's update the HTML and add some basic styling:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Personal Document Collection Form</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
        }
        .form-container {
            max-width: 600px;
            margin: auto;
            padding: 20px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        label {
            display: block;
            margin-bottom: 5px;
        }
        input[type="text"], input[type="number"], input[type="date"] {
            width: calc(100% - 22px);
            padding: 10px;
            margin-bottom: 15px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 20px;
            background-color: #007BFF;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
        .error {
            color: red;
            font-size: 0.9em;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="form-container">
        <h2>Personal Document Information</h2>
        <form id="documentForm" action="/submit_form" method="post" enctype="multipart/form-data">
            <label for="documentType">Document Type:</label>
            <select id="documentType" name="documentType" required>
                <option value="driverLicense">Driver's License</option>
                <option value="passport">Passport</option>
            </select>
            <span class="error" id="documentTypeError"></span>

            <label for="documentNumber">Document Number:</label>
            <input type="text" id="documentNumber" name="documentNumber" placeholder="Enter document number" required>
            <span class="error" id="documentNumberError"></span>

            <label for="expiryDate">Expiry Date (YYYY-MM-DD):</label>
            <input type="date" id="expiryDate" name="expiryDate" required>
            <span class="error" id="expiryDateError"></span>

            <label for="issuingAuthority">Issuing Authority:</label>
            <input type="text" id="issuingAuthority" name="issuingAuthority" placeholder="Enter issuing authority" required>
            <span class="error" id="issuingAuthorityError"></span>

            <button type="submit">Submit</button>
        </form>
    </div>

    <script>
        document.getElementById('documentForm').addEventListener('submit', function(event) {
            event.preventDefault(); // Prevent form submission

            const documentType = document.getElementById('documentType');
            const documentNumber = document.getElementById('documentNumber');
            const expiryDate = document.getElementById('expiryDate');
            const issuingAuthority = document.getElementById('issuingAuthority');

            const documentTypeError = document.getElementById('documentTypeError');
            const documentNumberError = document.getElementById('documentNumberError');
            const expiryDateError = document.getElementById('expiryDateError');
            const issuingAuthorityError = document.getElementById('issuingAuthorityError');

            // Clear previous error messages
            documentTypeError.textContent = '';
            documentNumberError.textContent = '';
            expiryDateError.textContent = '';
            issuingAuthorityError.textContent = '';

            // Validate document type
            if (!documentType.value) {
                documentTypeError.textContent = 'Please select a document type';
                return;
            }

            // Validate document number
            const documentNumberPattern = /^[A-Za-z0-9]{1,20}$/; // Simple pattern for alphanumeric characters
            if (!documentNumberPattern.test(documentNumber.value)) {
                documentNumberError.textContent = 'Invalid document number format';
                return;
            }

            // Validate expiry date
            const expiryDateValue = new Date(expiryDate.value);
            if (isNaN(expiryDateValue.getTime())) {
                expiryDateError.textContent = 'Invalid date format';
                return;
            }

            // Validate issuing authority
            if (!issuingAuthority.value) {
                issuingAuthorityError.textContent = 'Please enter the issuing authority';
                return;
            }

            // If all validations pass, submit the form
            this.submit();
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:

1. **HTML and Basic Styling**:
   - Added error message spans (`<span class="error">`) to display validation errors.
   - Updated the form to include client-side validation logic.

2. **JavaScript Client-Side Validation**:
   - Added an event listener to the form's `submit` event.
   - Prevents the form from submitting immediately.
   - Validates each field and displays error messages if the input is invalid.
   - Uses regular expressions and date validation to ensure the input meets specific criteria.

3. **Server-Side Validation**:
   - On the server side, you would need to validate the same fields again. Here’s a basic example using Node.js and Express:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const bodyParser = require('body-parser');
const app = express();

app.use(bodyParser.urlencoded({ extended: true }));

app.post('/submit_form', (req, res) => {
    const { documentType, documentNumber, expiryDate, issuingAuthority } = req.body;

    // Server-side validation
    if (!documentType) {
        return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Document type is required' });
    }

    const documentNumberPattern = /^[A-Za-z0-9]{1,20}$/;
    if (!documentNumberPattern.test(documentNumber)) {
        return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid document number format' });
    }

    const expiryDateValue = new Date(expiryDate);
    if (isNaN(expiryDateValue.getTime())) {
        return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid date format' });
    }

    if (!issuingAuthority) {
        return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Issuing authority is required' });
    }

    // If all validations pass, process the data
    res.json({ success: true, data: req.body });
});

app.listen(3000, () => {
    console.log('Server is running on port 3000');
});
```

### Explanation of Server-Side Validation:

1. **Express Setup**:
   - Use `body-parser` middleware to parse incoming request bodies.
   - Define a route for handling the form submission.

2. **Validation Logic**:
   - Check if the required fields are present.
   - Use regular expressions and date validation to ensure the input meets specific criteria.
   - Return appropriate HTTP status codes and error messages if validation fails.

By combining client-side and server-side validation, you can ensure that the data collected is both secure and accurate.

